# Day 13 - Securing Linux Network Services with iptables

## Project Overview

On Day 13 of my **#100DaysOfDevOps** challenge, I learned how to secure backend Linux servers using **iptables**, the native firewall framework in Linux. This lab was built directly
on the previous day's troubleshooting exercise by moving from identifying firewall issues to implementing firewall policies that protect production services.

In this project, I configured firewall rules to restrict access to an Apache web service running on port **6000**, ensuring that only the **Load Balancer (LBR)** 
could communicate with the application servers while blocking all other incoming traffic.

---

## Project Objectives

The requirements for this lab were:

* Install **iptables** and its required services on all application servers.
* Allow only the **Load Balancer** to access Apache on port **6000**.
* Block access to port **6000** from every other source.
* Ensure firewall rules persist after system reboot.

---

# Why This Matters

In a production environment, backend application servers should never be directly exposed to users or the internet.

Instead, requests should follow this architecture:

```text
                Internet
                    │
            Load Balancer (LBR)
                    │
        ┌───────────┼───────────┐
        │           │           │
    App Server1  App Server2  App Server3
```

The Load Balancer becomes the only entry point into the application infrastructure.

This approach provides several benefits:

* Reduces the attack surface
* Prevents direct access to backend servers
* Centralizes traffic management
* Improves security and scalability
* Aligns with the Principle of Least Privilege

