# Implementation Steps

## 1. Installed iptables Services

The firewall service was installed on each application server.

```bash
sudo yum install -y iptables-services
```

The `iptables-services` package allows firewall rules to be saved and automatically restored after system reboot.

---

## 2. Identified the Load Balancer IP Address

Before creating firewall rules, I identified the trusted Load Balancer IP address.

```bash
cat /etc/hosts
```

This IP was used as the only trusted source allowed to communicate with the application servers on port **6000**.

---

## 3. Allowed Traffic from the Load Balancer

A rule was inserted at the top of the firewall chain to allow incoming TCP traffic on port **6000** from the Load Balancer.

```bash
sudo iptables -I INPUT \
-s <LBR_IP> \
-p tcp \
--dport 6000 \
-j ACCEPT
```

Using `-I` inserts the rule at the beginning of the chain, ensuring it is evaluated before any blocking rules.

---

## 4. Blocked All Other Incoming Traffic

After allowing the trusted host, a second rule was appended to drop all remaining traffic destined for port **6000**.

```bash
sudo iptables -A INPUT \
-p tcp \
--dport 6000 \
-j DROP
```

This ensures that only requests originating from the Load Balancer are accepted.

---

## 5. Verified Firewall Rules

Firewall rules were reviewed to confirm they were applied in the correct order.

```bash
sudo iptables -L INPUT -n --line-numbers
```

Expected rule order:

```text
1 ACCEPT tcp -- LBR_IP --> Port 6000

2 DROP   tcp -- Anywhere --> Port 6000
```

Rule order is critical because **iptables evaluates rules sequentially and stops processing once a match is found**.

---

## 6. Saved Firewall Configuration

To ensure firewall rules survive a reboot, they were saved and the iptables service was enabled.

```bash
sudo service iptables save

sudo systemctl enable iptables

sudo systemctl start iptables
```

Without saving the configuration, firewall rules would be lost after restarting the server.

